Critical Finding: Redundant Query Patterns
1. QUERY_HISTORY — Queried 150 times across 16 files
This is by far the worst offender. The same underlying view is hit with slight variations in:

cost_center_sql.py — warehouse cost attribution (lines 155, 232)
cost_center_explain_view.py — user breakdown, query-type breakdown, hourly allocation (lines 167, 193, 220)
cost_center_attribution_view.py — cost allocation by query type (line 104)
cost_center_chargeback_view.py — chargeback split (line 121)
cost_center_user_leaderboard_view.py — top users by cost (line 88)
contention_center.py — queued/blocked queries, hot queries (lines 204, 317)
dba_control_room/data.py — morning cockpit, failure triage, error rate (lines 346, 357, 652, 677, 700, 720, 737)
query_analysis.py — performance deep-dive (lines 134, 780, 845, 855)
query_investigation_root_cause.py — root cause drill (line 467)
query_search.py — full-text query search
detailed_diagnosis.py — slow query diagnosis (line 204)
Pattern problem: At least 6 of these queries scan the same date range and warehouse filter with different GROUP BYs or WHEREs. They could be a single wide pre-aggregation queried differently.

2. WAREHOUSE_METERING_HISTORY — 62 references across 7 files
Cost center overview, cost contract cockpit, warehouse health, DBA morning cockpit all independently query the same hourly metering data.
Multiple sections compute "daily credits burned by warehouse" independently.
3. Cortex usage views — UNION ALL pattern duplicated 8 times
In cortex_monitor.py, the pattern:

sql
SELECT ... FROM SNOWFLAKE.ACCOUNT_USAGE.CORTEX_CODE_SNOWSIGHT_USAGE_HISTORY
UNION ALL
SELECT ... FROM SNOWFLAKE.ACCOUNT_USAGE.CORTEX_CODE_CLI_USAGE_HISTORY
appears at lines 478/482, 577/581, 1073/1077, 1277/1281, 1345/1349, 1478/1482, 1606/1610 — 7 duplicate UNION ALL blocks with slightly different SELECT lists or date ranges.

4. USERS JOIN — repeated 12+ times
LEFT JOIN SNOWFLAKE.ACCOUNT_USAGE.USERS u ON ... = u.USER_ID appears at least 12 times in cortex_monitor.py alone, plus in other files. The user dimension never changes.

Query Budget Analysis
The performance.py budget system reveals the actual render-time constraint:

Context	Budget (queries allowed)
First paint (page load)	1
Warm first paint (revisit)	0
Section route change	0
Evidence click	1
Admin click	3
Decision bootstrap	20
Account usage fallback	1
This means the app intends to fire 0-1 queries on page load — but the architecture relies on the user clicking "Load Evidence" to trigger actual ACCOUNT_USAGE queries. The budget system is a workaround for the fact that queries are too expensive to pre-load.

Key constraint: ACCOUNT_USAGE_TARGETED_SCAN_ALLOWED = False and COST_WORKBENCH_FIRST_PAINT_ALLOWED = False — these are explicitly blocking render-time queries because they can't afford the latency.

