Recommendations (Priority Order)
P0 — Eliminate the QUERY_HISTORY bottleneck
Create DT_QUERY_DAILY_SUMMARY as a dynamic table:

text
warehouse, user_name, query_type, execution_status, date
→ query_count, total_execution_time_ms, total_credits_used, 
  bytes_scanned, rows_produced, error_count
Refresh every hour with 45-minute lag. This eliminates 80%+ of the QUERY_HISTORY direct scans.

P1 — Consolidate Cortex monitoring into a single cached loader
Replace 7 UNION ALL blocks in cortex_monitor.py with one @st.cache_data(ttl=600) function that returns the full Cortex usage DataFrame, then filter/group per-workflow.

P2 — Pre-join the USERS dimension
Load SNOWFLAKE.ACCOUNT_USAGE.USERS once at session start (it's tiny — typically <10K rows). Join in Python instead of repeating LEFT JOIN USERS in every SQL string.

P3 — Dynamic table for WAREHOUSE_METERING_HISTORY daily rollup
DT_WAREHOUSE_DAILY_CREDITS with warehouse_name, date, credits_used, credits_cloud, idle_minutes. Serves 7 files.

P4 — Replace "Load Evidence" with stale-cache-first
Use st.cache_data with a 5-minute TTL so pages render immediately with cached data, then offer "Refresh" to re-query. This eliminates the empty-state UX problem while still respecting query budgets.

Bottom Line
The app references 46 distinct ACCOUNT_USAGE views across 38 section files with ~460 total references. The single biggest problem is QUERY_HISTORY being independently queried ~150 times across 16 files with overlapping date ranges and filters. Five dynamic tables would eliminate approximately 70% of render-time query volume and convert the "click to load" pattern from a necessary performance workaround into an optional detail drill.
